05700nam a22008175i 9780812206241DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979623093  a97808122062417 a10.9783/97808122062412doi  a(DE-B1597)449517  a(OCoLC)824522202  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a320.513097941 aBell, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCalifornia Crucible :bThe Forging of Modern American Liberalism /cJonathan Bell. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Culture in Modern America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Placing California in Post-World War II American Politics -- tChapter 1. Politics and Party in California at Mid-Century -- tChapter 2. Building the Democratic Party in the 1940s -- tChapter 3. The Stevenson Effect -- tChapter 4. A Democratic Order -- tChapter 5. Turning Point: California Politics in the 1950s -- tChapter 6. The Liberal Moment -- tChapter 7. Democratic Politics and the Brown Administration -- tChapter 8. Welfare Reform and the Idea of the Family -- tChapter 9. Culture Wars, Politics, and Power -- tChapter 10. The Legacy of the Democratic Party Renaissance -- tEpilogue: Liberal Politics in California in an “Era of Limits” -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the three decades following World War II, the Golden State was not only the fastest-growing state in the Union but also the site of significant political change. From the late 1940s through the mid-1970s, a generation of liberal activists transformed the political landscape of California, ending Republican dominance of state politics and eventually setting the tone for the Democratic Party nationwide.In California Crucible, Jonathan Bell chronicles this dramatic story of postwar liberalism—from early grassroots organizing and the election of Pat Brown as governor in 1958 to the civil rights campaigns of the 1960s and the campaigns against the New Right in the 1970s. As Bell argues, the emergent "California liberalism" was a distinctly post-New Deal phenomenon that drew on the ambitious ideals of the New Deal but adapted them to a diverse population. The result was a broad coalition that sought to extend social democracy to marginalized groups—such as gay rights and civil rights organizations—that had not been well served by the Democratic Party in earlier decades. In building this coalition, liberal activists forged an ideology capable of bringing Latino farm workers, African American civil rights activists, and wealthy suburban homemakers into a shared political project.By exploring California Democrats' largely successful attempts to link economic rights to civil rights and serve the needs of diverse groups, Bell challenges common assumptions about the rise of the New Right and the decline of American liberalism in the postwar era. As Bell shows, by the end of the 1970s California had become the spiritual home of the liberal wing of the Democratic Party as much as that of the Reagan Revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHISTORYzUnited Statesx20th century. 0aLiberalismvCaliforniaxHistoryx20th century. 0aLiberalismzCaliforniaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiberalismzUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aLiberalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn P